# 🔥 Time Travel Methods

---

# 1️⃣ Method 1: Using OFFSET (Go Back Few Minutes)

View table 5 minutes ago:

```sql
SELECT *
FROM ORDERS_TT
AT (OFFSET => -60*5);
```

👉 This shows table state 5 minutes earlier.

---

# 2️⃣ Method 2: Using TIMESTAMP

```sql
SELECT *
FROM ORDERS_TT
AT (TIMESTAMP => CURRENT_TIMESTAMP() - INTERVAL '5 MINUTE');
```

---

# 3️⃣ Method 3: BEFORE (STATEMENT)

Recover data before last DELETE:

```sql
SELECT *
FROM ORDERS_TT
BEFORE (STATEMENT => LAST_QUERY_ID());
```

Or use specific query ID:

```sql
SELECT *
FROM ORDERS_TT
BEFORE (STATEMENT => '01b12345-0000-0000-0000-000000000000');
```

---

# 🔥 Restore Deleted Data

Suppose you deleted rows accidentally.

Recover them:

```sql
INSERT INTO ORDERS_TT
SELECT *
FROM ORDERS_TT
AT (OFFSET => -60*5);
```

---

# 🔥 UNDROP TABLE (Very Important)

If you drop table:

```sql
DROP TABLE ORDERS_TT;
```

Recover it:

```sql
UNDROP TABLE ORDERS_TT;
```

Works only within retention period.

---

# 🔥 CLONE Table at Previous Time (Powerful Feature)

```sql
CREATE TABLE ORDERS_CLONE
CLONE ORDERS_TT
AT (OFFSET => -60*5);
```

Now you have snapshot of old data.

---

# 🧠 How to Check Retention Period

```sql
SHOW PARAMETERS LIKE 'DATA_RETENTION_TIME_IN_DAYS'
IN TABLE ORDERS_TT;
```

Typical:

| Edition    | Retention |
| ---------- | --------- |
| Standard   | 1 day     |
| Enterprise | 1–90 days |

